Y the rude bridge that arched the flood, Their flag to April’s breeze unfurled,

Here once the embattled farmers stood, And fired the shot heard round the world,

The foe long since in silence slept ; Alike the conqueror silent sleeps 3 And time the ruined bridge has swept Down the dark stream which seaward creeps.

On this green bank, by this soft stream, We set to-day a votive stone ;

That· memory may their deed redeem, When, like our sires, our sons are gone.

Spirit, that made those heroes dare

The shaft we raise to them and thee.

He may divest himself of it; he may creep into a corner, and abdicate his kingdom, as most men do; but he is entitled to the world by his constitution.
